06679nam a22010335i 9783110698190DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021942344  a97831106981907 a10.1515/97831106981902doi  a(DE-B1597)546715  a(OCoLC)1290485459  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBT153.I47bT45 2022 7aREL0510002bisacsh04a231.422300aTemporality and Eternity :bNine Perspectives on God and Time /ced. by Marcus Schmücker, Michael T. Williams, Florian Fischer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VIII, 220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tTemporal and timeless deity -- tFrom divine timemaker to divine watchmaker -- tTime’s arrow, relativity and God’s eternity: From the limitedness of creatures to the asymmetric structure of the worldline -- tGod, the grandfather of time: Time and the absolute in the thought of Philo of Alexandria -- tThe Muslim theologian Ibn Taymiyyah on God, creation and time -- tHistorical eternity: The approaches of Wolfhart Pannenberg and Hans Urs von Balthasar -- tOn the relation between God and time in the later theistic Vedānta of Madhva, Jayatīrtha and Veṅkaṭanātha -- tAnalytic philosophy of time in Early Modern India -- tNon-persistence in time: A Buddhist account of intrinsic nature -- tContributors -- tAuthors/Persons -- tWorks -- tKey-terms0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs time a creation of God? How can God be considered eternal, if he is responsible for the existence of time? Is God temporal or is he timeless? The relationship between God and time has been an object of inquiry in philosophical and theological traditions around the world for centuries. This volume takes up these and other questions, presenting a range of answers not only as brought forth in European philosophical traditions and in early Christianity, Judaism and Islam, but also positions taken by mediaeval Indian theologians and in the influential traditions of early Buddhism. Traditionally, discussions have focused on questions such as whether time is a necessary concomitant of God’s existence, or whether time should be identified with God. But there is a further question: did these traditions develop their own unrelated and independent view of God and time? Or are there similarities in their reflections? This volume, with contributions of scholars from various relevant fields, offers a novel approach to these inquiries. When taken as a whole, it provides new momentum to contemplation on an age-old enigma.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTimexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 4aEwigkeit. 4aGott. 4aKontinuität. 4aVergänglichkeit. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh  aContinuity.  aEternity.  aGod.  aMomentariness.1 aFischer, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Florian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrössl, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoover, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMullins, R.T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSakai, Masamichi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaudek, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmücker, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmücker, Marcus, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchulz, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStr